adversity, these water hoses,

00:03:10.590 --> 00:03:11.280
I heard--

00:03:11.280 --> 00:03:14.430
there was an issue of
control, resistance.

00:03:14.430 --> 00:03:16.860
This border wall
suggests there's

00:03:16.860 --> 00:03:18.660
something about being
in and out and not

00:03:18.660 --> 00:03:21.090
being able to attain something.

00:03:21.090 --> 00:03:24.290
And then the X Games--

00:03:24.290 --> 00:03:25.620
what'd you call it?

00:03:25.620 --> 00:03:26.250
Cheerleading?

00:03:26.250 --> 00:03:27.745
Extreme-- ultimate cheerleading.

00:03:27.745 --> 00:03:28.620
Extreme cheerleading.

00:03:28.620 --> 00:03:30.286
So there's an activity,
but then there's

00:03:30.286 --> 00:03:34.680
something else that
pushes it or ramps it up.

00:03:34.680 --> 00:03:37.060
Add some context here.

00:03:37.060 --> 00:03:40.170
This is a still image from
a performance by performance

00:03:40.170 --> 00:03:41.710
artist Dread Scott.

00:03:41.710 --> 00:03:44.400
The title of the work is
called, On the Impossibility

00:03:44.400 --> 00:03:48.900
of Freedom in a Country Founded
on Slavery and Genocide.

00:03:48.900 --> 00:03:51.300
And he's referencing
a range of events,

00:03:51.300 --> 00:03:53.340
but specifically
a particular event

00:03:53.340 --> 00:03:56.730
in the '60s where
there was a protest

00:03:56.730 --> 00:04:00.040
against racial injustice.

00:04:00.040 --> 00:04:04.620
Where the authorities
used water hoses,

00:04:04.620 --> 00:04:08.730
high-powered water hoses to
push back African Americans.

00:04:08.730 --> 00:04:11.160
This was not a single
event, these kinds of things

00:04:11.160 --> 00:04:12.600
happen all the time in the '60s.

00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:14.725
So this is part of Dread
Scott's performance,

00:04:14.725 --> 00:04:16.320
this is a still from
his performance.

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:20.940
I find it remarkable listening
to even the comedy trailer,

00:04:20.940 --> 00:04:24.090
that you were picking
up on elements of what

00:04:24.090 --> 00:04:25.712
his performance--

00:04:25.712 --> 00:04:28.170
what he intended his performance
to be about, but also what

00:04:28.170 --> 00:04:31.650
other people have interpreted
his performance to be about.

00:04:31.650 --> 00:04:35.100
Charles Garoian is a performance
artist an art educator

00:04:35.100 --> 00:04:39.720
who also taught high school in
the Bay Area in San Francisco.

00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:44.040
And he taught his students
in late '60s and the '70s--

00:04:44.040 --> 00:04:45.780
into the '80s
actually I believe--

00:04:45.780 --> 00:04:47.570
about performance
art and happenings,

00:04:47.570 --> 00:04:51.420
and the ways in which our
bodies can perform symbolically

00:04:51.420 --> 00:04:53.700
to construct works
of art that relate

00:04:53.700 --> 00:04:57.300
to social issues
and cultural issues.

00:04:57.300 --> 00:05:01.000
So his work is documented
in several of his books,

00:05:01.000 --> 00:05:03.000
one of which is called
Performing Pedagogy where

00:05:03.000 --> 00:05:06.840
he interprets several works
of art and performance art

00:05:06.840 --> 00:05:09.270
and then provides
a set of activities

00:05:09.270 --> 00:05:12.810
that teachers and their
students can perform

00:05:12.810 --> 00:05:15.360
to learn some of
the basic structures

00:05:15.360 --> 00:05:17.250
or some elements
of performance art

00:05:17.250 --> 00:05:21.270
using one's body as
an artistic medium,

00:05:21.270 --> 00:05:24.390
but also a way in which to
comment on social issues.

00:05:24.390 --> 00:05:28.260
But it's the idea of using our
bodies as symbolic vehicles

00:05:28.260 --> 00:05:29.430
that become powerful.

00:05:29.430 --> 00:05:31.260
And also the ways that
our bodies can move

00:05:31.260 --> 00:05:33.000
and the ways in which
our bodies interact

00:05:33.000 --> 00:05:35.090
with other objects
or other ideas,

00:05:35.090 --> 00:05:39.060
the way in which we might
maybe think of taking our body,

00:05:39.060 --> 00:05:42.070
doing something to it,
doing something else to it.

00:05:42.070 --> 00:05:48.120
So there's an activity that
I often do with my students--

00:05:48.120 --> 00:05:50.160
undergrad, graduate
students, students

00:05:50.160 --> 00:05:53.230
who are learning to
be teachers that I

00:05:53.230 --> 00:05:54.480
borrowed from Charles Garoian.

00:05:54.480 --> 00:05:58.780
Here's a still image of
one student doing this.

00:05:58.780 --> 00:06:04.520
And what I'd like you to do
is to identify a statement.

00:06:04.520 --> 00:06:08.730
Could be an excerpt, it
could be song lyrics,

00:06:08.730 --> 00:06:15.420
it could be a poem, but it needs
to be a set of words that--

00:06:15.420 --> 00:06:18.360
ideally it's a text or a
sentence or several phrases--

00:06:18.360 --> 00:06:23.390
that you could or
someone else could say

00:06:23.390 --> 00:06:26.526
within a 30-second time period.

00:06:26.526 --> 00:06:28.400
So borrowing from Charles
Garoian's approach,

00:06:28.400 --> 00:06:32.350
one of the activities is
to take an image and--

00:06:32.350 --> 00:06:38.060
a body, and the body engages
in a repetitive motion,

00:06:38.060 --> 00:06:39.970
a repetitive activity.

00:06:39.970 --> 00:06:43.990
And the ideas that that body
in motion in relationship

00:06:43.990 --> 00:06:46.990
to or in juxtaposition with
or in critique or conversation

00:06:46.990 --> 00:06:51.940
with that image will inherently
start to construct or suggest

00:06:51.940 --> 00:06:53.747
different interpretations,
just like what

00:06:53.747 --> 00:06:55.330
you did when you saw
the image and you

00:06:55.330 --> 00:06:57.200
added some text to that.

00:06:57.200 --> 00:06:59.920
But there's a third
element, and that's the text

00:06:59.920 --> 00:07:01.180
that you've come up with.

00:07:01.180 --> 00:07:03.360
So what is going to happen--

00:07:03.360 --> 00:07:06.080
so here's another student
doing something similar.

00:07:06.080 --> 00:07:09.424
So what's going to happen is,
I'm going to hit this button,

00:07:09.424 --> 00:07:10.840
and then I'm going
to go over here

00:07:10.840 --> 00:07:12.256
and I'm going to
start performing.

00:07:12.256 --> 00:07:15.100
I'm going to do a repetitive
motion for 30 seconds.

00:07:15.100 --> 00:07:18.494
When I get over there, you're
going to speak your text.

00:07:18.494 --> 00:07:19.410
AUDIENCE: Oh, my text?

00:07:19.410 --> 00:07:19.880
STEPHEN CARPENTER: Yes.

00:07:19.880 --> 00:07:21.170
AUDIENCE: Oh, I thought
I was reading your text.

00:07:21.170 --> 00:07:22.390
STEPHEN CARPENTER: No, no.

00:07:22.390 --> 00:07:24.280
Oh, you would rather
