00:09:21.080 --> 00:09:22.300
STEPHEN CARPENTER: OK, nice.

00:09:22.300 --> 00:09:23.920
So why would I do
something like that?

00:09:23.920 --> 00:09:27.557
Well, at the end of the
semester, the students in one

00:09:27.557 --> 00:09:29.390
of my graduate classes
I teach at Penn State

00:09:29.390 --> 00:09:31.360
and also at Vermont
College of Fine Arts,

00:09:31.360 --> 00:09:35.686
after going through that process
of the randomness of making

00:09:35.686 --> 00:09:37.060
those connections,
they then have

00:09:37.060 --> 00:09:40.540
to go through the process of
intentionally combining image,

00:09:40.540 --> 00:09:43.760
text, and body movement
for a public performance

00:09:43.760 --> 00:09:45.560
that lasts at
least five minutes.

00:09:45.560 --> 00:09:49.579
So these are-- the top row
are stills from one video,

00:09:49.579 --> 00:09:51.370
the bottom row are
stills from another one,

00:09:51.370 --> 00:09:54.400
and the one at the top,
the student was interested

00:09:54.400 --> 00:09:58.060
in the idea that someone told
her at one point something

00:09:58.060 --> 00:10:02.980
like, there have
never been any wars--

00:10:02.980 --> 00:10:04.906
international wars on US soil.

00:10:04.906 --> 00:10:06.780
And she thought, this
doesn't make any sense,

00:10:06.780 --> 00:10:08.280
and a history teacher
told her that.

00:10:08.280 --> 00:10:10.630
So the idea was that this
performance speaks back

00:10:10.630 --> 00:10:12.676
to that, and this was
performed in Philadelphia.

00:10:12.676 --> 00:10:14.800
And so you can see in these
three different images,

00:10:14.800 --> 00:10:16.425
she's using her body
in different ways.

00:10:16.425 --> 00:10:17.710
She's holding a photo of--

00:10:17.710 --> 00:10:21.200
a satellite photo
of a plane bombing.

00:10:21.200 --> 00:10:24.720
She created almost a little
memorial and burial for this

00:10:24.720 --> 00:10:27.580
and has watered it generously
and then puts her own body down

00:10:27.580 --> 00:10:28.510
in this bench.

00:10:28.510 --> 00:10:31.390
That it's essentially a
whispering bench where she

00:10:31.390 --> 00:10:34.326
she's sitting at one end and
can whisper into the corner,

00:10:34.326 --> 00:10:35.950
and the person sitting
at the other end

00:10:35.950 --> 00:10:37.660
can hear what she's saying.

00:10:37.660 --> 00:10:39.250
And the one at the
bottom is a student

00:10:39.250 --> 00:10:42.940
who performed outside
of Karachi-- that's

00:10:42.940 --> 00:10:46.400
at Carnegie Hall, in
front of Carnegie Hall.

00:10:46.400 --> 00:10:50.420
And symbolically speaking
to a death in her family,

00:10:50.420 --> 00:10:54.650
but also her own musical
aspirations and the way

00:10:54.650 --> 00:10:57.690
in which they relate
to her own life,

00:10:57.690 --> 00:11:01.860
but also she was equating
it to gun violence.

00:11:01.860 --> 00:11:03.890
And so she was
cleaning the clarinet

00:11:03.890 --> 00:11:06.140
and puts it in this
case in various ways

00:11:06.140 --> 00:11:07.270
that make you suggest--

00:11:07.270 --> 00:11:09.980
they suggest, is this a
musical instrument or is it

00:11:09.980 --> 00:11:13.760
an implement for an
instrument of killing?

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:17.960
So these are some outgrowths
from that quick assignment

00:11:17.960 --> 00:11:19.910
that we did.

00:11:19.910 --> 00:11:22.670
So in summary, you
could engage learners

00:11:22.670 --> 00:11:26.410
like we've done today
in any of these ways,

00:11:26.410 --> 00:11:28.960
or you could do boring stuff.

00:11:28.960 --> 00:11:31.140
It's really up to you.

